04167nam a22006135i 9780292793514DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927935147 a10.7560/7211972doi  a(DE-B1597)587327  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aLC2410.I74bG74 2010 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a371.8281 aGreenberg, Ela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPreparing the Mothers of Tomorrow :bEducation and Islam in Mandate Palestine /cEla Greenberg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (293 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Educating Girls in Late Ottoman Palestine -- tChapter 2. Removing “the Long-standing Prejudice against Girls’ Education” -- tChapter 3. Reading the Bible and Wearing the Veil -- tChapter 4. “The Love of the Nation Is from Faith” -- tChapter 5. Learning to Be “The Mothers of Tomorrow” -- tChapter 6. The Mothers of Tomorrow in the Public Sp here -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the late nineteenth century onward, men and women throughout the Middle East discussed, debated, and negotiated the roles of young girls and women in producing modern nations. In Palestine, girls' education was pivotal to discussions about motherhood. Their education was seen as having the potential to transform the family so that it could meet both modern and nationalist expectations. Ela Greenberg offers the first study to examine the education of Muslim girls in Palestine from the end of the Ottoman administration through the British colonial rule. Relying upon extensive archival sources, official reports, the Palestinian Arabic press, and interviews, she describes the changes that took place in girls' education during this time. Greenberg describes how local Muslims, often portrayed as indifferent to girls' education, actually responded to the inadequacies of existing government education by sending their daughters to missionary schools despite religious tensions, or by creating their own private nationalist institutions. Greenberg shows that members of all socioeconomic classes understood the triad of girls' education, modernity, and the nationalist struggle, as educated girls would become the "mothers of tomorrow" who would raise nationalist and modern children. While this was the aim of the various schools in Palestine, not all educated Muslim girls followed this path, as some used their education, even if it was elementary at best, to become teachers, nurses, and activists in women's organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMuslim girlsxEducationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslim womenxEducationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793514/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK